text: 12th Avenue, east side, from W. 31st (right) to 34th Streets, showing the N.Y. Central Railroad yards. The 1-story sheds in the foreground are located between 31st and 32nd Streets. On the left are the 2-story hay lofts on the north side of 33rd Street. March 17, 1929. P. L. Sperr.

Twelfth Avenue, east side, between W. 31st and 32nd Streets, showing a portion of the New York Central Railroad yards on this westerly margin of Manhattan. The photographer is viewing mainly eastward to show the distant Empire State Building being belittled by a rubbish incinerator's smoke stack. A latter photo will show the circular loop of the new elevated railroad bed at this location. April 22, 1931. P. L. Sperr.

Twelfth and Thirteenth Avenues, east side, from 31st to 29th Streets. Twelfth begins at 30th Street, branching off from Thirteenth Avenue. It was originally planned to have Thirteenth Avenue continue north of 30th Street and west of Twelfth Avenue, on land to be made by filling along the shore but this plan was never carried out. For practical purposes, Thirteenth Avenue is a souther extension of Twelfth, but slightly towards the east instead of being parallel to Eleventh. May 30, 1934. P. L. Sperr.
